                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Wrist Flexors</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534779/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">wrist flexors</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, located on the inside of the forearm, stabilize your wrists during the cross-body tricep extension. These muscles activate to keep your wrists from bending backward when gripping the cable handles. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For example, while gripping a heavy object, the wrist flexors curl your fingers and stabilize the wrist. Proper engagement of the wrist flexors maintains a </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10777545/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">strong grip</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and supports overall movement efficiency. </span></p><h3><b>Wrist Extensors</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534805/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">wrist extensors</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, found on the outside of the forearm, also stabilize the wrists during the cross-body tricep extension. These muscles work to keep your wrists straight and aligned with your forearms. When straightening your elbows during this exercise, the wrist extensors prevent your wrists from collapsing forward.</span></p><p><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28759532/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Engaging these muscles</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> ensures proper wrist alignment, providing stability and control throughout the movement. This support is essential for performing the exercise correctly and safely.</span></p>                        </div>
